    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to predict absolute hemolysis levels across operating conditions for a centrifugal blood pump used as a ventricular assist device (VAD). Model influence is HIGH (model is primary basis for hemolysis acceptance); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect prediction could result in chronic patient hemolysis requiring clinical intervention). Model Risk Level 5 — the highest in the Morrison assessment.",
    "deviceClass": "Class III",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou2-vad",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to predict absolute hemolysis index values for a Class III VAD device across 5 flow-speed combinations. Results must demonstrate hemolysis below absolute clinical threshold (not relative to predicate). Requires Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification on hemolysis predictions.",
    "modelInfluence": "High",
    "name": "COU2: Ventricular assist device use (Class III)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/vad-hemolysis-absolute-threshold",
      "type": "Claim",
      "name": "CFD model predicts absolute hemolysis index below clinical threshold across all VAD operating conditions",
      "description": "This claim asserts that the calibrated CFD hemolysis model, incorporating the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law damage accumulation formulation and Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification over inlet boundary conditions and fluid viscosity, produces predicted Normalised Index of Hemolysis (NIH) values that remain below the clinical acceptance threshold of 0.01 g/100 L across all five evaluated flow-speed operating points (3 L/min at 3000 RPM, 4 L/min at 3500 RPM, 5 L/min at 4000 RPM, 5 L/min at 4500 RPM, 6 L/min at 5000 RPM). The claim is grounded in a body of work comprising: (i) grid-convergence studies on three mesh densities (4.2 M, 9.8 M, and 21.4 M cells) demonstrating GCI below 3.5% for NIH; (ii) validation against FDA inter-laboratory hemolysis bench data showing agreement within experimental scatter for four of five operating points; (iii) sensitivity analyses identifying inlet turbulence intensity and erythrocyte mechanical fragility coefficient as dominant uncertainty contributors; and (iv) a 2000-sample Latin Hypercube Monte Carlo sweep confirming 95th-percentile NIH predictions remain 18% below threshold. The evidence base is described in Morrison et al. (2023) and the associated FDA submission dossier. All supporting computations were performed with OpenFOAM v9 under SQA protocol QA-CFD-2022-07.",
      "purpose": "Provide the primary credibility assertion linking model outputs to regulatory acceptance criteria for Class III VAD hemolysis evaluation.",
      "scope": "Applicable to the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry at MRL 5; not transferable to patient-specific geometries without re-assessment."
    }
  ],
